2
00:01:13.575 --> 00:01:14.825
It's gonna be great.

3
00:01:14.826 --> 00:01:16.577
Sure. what could go wrong?

4
00:01:16.578 --> 00:01:18.538
- She's gonna love you.
- Uh-huh.

5
00:01:20.206 --> 00:01:22.500
Do you think you'll see
NYU while you're in town?

6
00:01:24.211 --> 00:01:25.212
Maybe.

7
00:01:25.712 --> 00:01:27.171
She can't go to NYU.

8
00:01:27.172 --> 00:01:29.299
How would she be home
for dinner every night?

9
00:01:29.841 --> 00:01:31.508
Your dad told me
you love theater.

10
00:01:31.509 --> 00:01:35.055
so I got us tickets to the revival
of <i>Barefoot in the Park</i> tomorrow.

11
00:01:36.473 --> 00:01:40.352
Neil Simon. right? He's a favorite
around here. How great is that?

12
00:01:42.646 --> 00:01:44.564
I thought it was just
gonna be us tomorrow.

13
00:01:47.234 --> 00:01:50.945
You know what? I'm pretty far
behind on that bowl for the Canners.

14
00:01:50.946 --> 00:01:52.821
I could use a quiet
night at the studio.

15
00:01:52.822 --> 00:01:56.033
- You two go without me.
- No. I'd like us all to go together.

16
00:01:56.034 --> 00:01:58.328
Sure. we'll do it next time.

17
00:02:03.291 --> 00:02:05.001
Say thank you for the tickets.

18
00:02:06.795 --> 00:02:09.631
Thanks. I have to
go to the bathroom.

19
00:02:16.429 --> 00:02:17.430
Yeah.

20
00:02:18.557 --> 00:02:19.808
It's gonna be great. huh?

21
00:02:21.851 --> 00:02:22.852
You're doing fine.

22
00:02:23.353 --> 00:02:25.188
I know exactly how
I'm doing. thank you.

23
00:02:30.277 --> 00:02:32.528
- She seems great.
- You mean that?

24
00:02:32.529 --> 00:02:34.030
She's her own person.

25
00:02:35.031 --> 00:02:36.449
What could be better than that?

26
00:02:38.201 --> 00:02:39.202
Nothing.

27
00:02:41.413 --> 00:02:43.623
Why would he make
up a fake life?

28
00:02:44.583 --> 00:02:48.544
I don't know. Maybe he
was trying to protect you.

29
00:02:48.545 --> 00:02:49.629
From what?

30
00:02:50.714 --> 00:02:51.882
I really don't know.

31
00:02:52.966 --> 00:02:55.969
- The only thing I know for certain...
- He lied to me.

32
00:02:57.470 --> 00:02:58.471
He lied to me too.

33
00:03:04.603 --> 00:03:09.357
So. I mean. if he changed his name.
that means he probably changed mine.

34
00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:11.735
Yeah.

35
00:03:13.236 --> 00:03:14.237
And my birthday.

36
00:03:15.071 --> 00:03:16.072
Probably.

37
00:03:19.951 --> 00:03:22.996
Seems like something a person
should know about themselves.

38
00:03:33.048 --> 00:03:34.507
- Bailey.
- What?

39
00:03:35.383 --> 00:03:36.843
What are you gonna say. Hannah?

40
00:03:37.677 --> 00:03:41.223
What the fuck could you possibly say
right now that would make any sense?

41
00:03:43.016 --> 00:03:45.852
Nothing. There's nothing to say.

42
00:03:50.815 --> 00:03:55.028
We should try and get some sleep.
We've got an early flight home.

43
00:03:56.321 --> 00:03:57.322
Excuse me?

44
00:03:58.073 --> 00:03:59.324
We're not gonna find him there.

45
00:04:04.746 --> 00:04:05.747
You were right.

46
00:04:06.831 --> 00:04:10.418
Something's here. I can feel it.

47
00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:14.881
So. you wanna stay?

48
00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:20.720
Yeah. I wanna stay.

49
00:04:38.613 --> 00:04:40.490
<i>You should've seen me at 15.</i>

50
00:04:40.991 --> 00:04:42.408
What color was your hair?

51
00:04:42.409 --> 00:04:46.496
Seriously. it wasn't pretty.
It's not easy without a mom.

52
00:04:52.919 --> 00:04:55.088
Thank God I had my grandfather.

53
00:04:55.881 --> 00:04:57.132
Yeah.

54
00:05:24.826 --> 00:05:26.118
<i>Deputy Bradford's office</i>.

55
00:05:26.119 --> 00:05:27.286
Yes. Is he in?

56
00:05:27.287 --> 00:05:29.748
<i>I'm afraid he's on vacation.
Would you like his voice mail?</i>

57
00:05:30.790 --> 00:05:31.832
Vacation?

58
00:05:31.833 --> 00:05:32.918
<i>Yes. ma'am.</i>

59
00:05:33.793 --> 00:05:35.170
Can I take a message?

60
00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:39.131
No. but you can put me in touch
with someone who can tell me

61
00:05:39.132 --> 00:05:42.719
what Deputy Bradford was doing waving
his badge in my face on his vacation.

62
00:05:45.639 --> 00:05:48.641
- Did you go see the Warriors?
- No. it wasn't that kind of trip. <i>mijo</i>.

63
00:05:48.642 --> 00:05:51.394
But I did catch the end of
last night's game on TV.

64
00:05:51.895 --> 00:05:55.356
- You see DeRozan dunk on Curry?
- Yeah. That was pretty.

65
00:05:55.357 --> 00:05:56.900
Hey. what were you
doing up so late?

66
00:05:57.901 --> 00:05:59.693
- Dad!
- Buddy. it was a school night.

67
00:05:59.694 --> 00:06:00.779
We talked about this. okay?

68
00:06:01.488 --> 00:06:03.990
Come on. Dad. It's the playoffs.

69
00:06:06.076 --> 00:06:09.621
Okay. we're not done here.

70
00:06:14.584 --> 00:06:15.418
This is Grady.

71
00:06:15.419 --> 00:06:16.586
How's spring break?

72
00:06:17.087 --> 00:06:18.004
<i>Excuse me?</i>

73
00:06:18.005 --> 00:06:20.839
Your office just told me you
were on vacation. It's funny.

74
00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:23.280
It sure didn't seem that way
when you were sitting on my dock.

75
00:06:24.928 --> 00:06:26.595
Hannah. I was there to help.

76
00:06:26.596 --> 00:06:28.639
<i>Then how about telling me
what's really going on?</i>

77
00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:32.310
Why are there no records of Owen before
he and Bailey moved to Sausalito?

78
00:06:32.894 --> 00:06:34.770
<i>What? Who told you that?</i>

79
00:06:34.771 --> 00:06:36.188
What does that matter?

80
00:06:36.189 --> 00:06:38.983
<i>Look. did it ever occur to you that
the man developing The Shop's software</i>

81
00:06:38.984 --> 00:06:41.528
<i>for erasing online paper trails
may have used it on himself?</i>

82
00:06:43.905 --> 00:06:46.907
If that software works. Avett
wouldn't be on trial for fraud.

83
00:06:46.908 --> 00:06:49.326
And I would still be
asleep in bed with Owen.

84
00:06:49.327 --> 00:06:52.496
unaware that he'd lied to me
about everything. apparently.

85
00:06:52.497 --> 00:06:53.622
That's not actually true.

86
00:06:53.623 --> 00:06:56.751
Is that right? Why did
Owen change his name?

87
00:06:58.628 --> 00:07:00.296
I think you're getting
ahead of yourself there.

88
00:07:00.297 --> 00:07:02.089
<i>I think you're not telling
me the whole story.</i>

89
00:07:02.090 --> 00:07:05.134
I'm just trying to keep Owen
safe. Owen and Bailey. And you.

90
00:07:05.135 --> 00:07:07.470
Well. I can take care
of myself. thank you.

91
00:07:08.179 --> 00:07:09.379
<i>Is that what you're doing now?</i>

92
00:07:11.016 --> 00:07:13.101
- What's that supposed to mean?
- <i>Where are you?</i>

93
00:07:14.477 --> 00:07:15.812
<i>Hannah?</i>

94
00:07:16.479 --> 00:07:17.479
I'm home.

95
00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:19.315
Yeah. if that were the case
the heavy Avett sent over

96
00:07:19.316 --> 00:07:21.942
to break into your house would
have been more disturbing.

97
00:07:21.943 --> 00:07:24.069
What? Avett sent someone to...

98
00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:27.156
Seriously. where
are you? A hotel?

99
00:07:27.157 --> 00:07:29.701
I'll send a deputy from the San
Francisco office to pick you up.

100
00:07:30.827 --> 00:07:32.495
Have you been watching my house?

101
00:07:33.121 --> 00:07:34.663
Where the hell are you. Hannah?

102
00:07:34.664 --> 00:07:36.041
Where are you worried I'll be?

103
00:07:43.715 --> 00:07:46.008
<i>It seems like something
a person should know.</i>

104
00:07:46.009 --> 00:07:48.303
<i>She doesn't know
what grade I'm in</i>.

105
00:08:17.415 --> 00:08:18.416
Hannah.

106
00:08:21.545 --> 00:08:22.879
What the hell happened here?

107
00:08:23.630 --> 00:08:25.757
She doesn't even know
what grade I'm in.

108
00:08:30.804 --> 00:08:31.805
Let me see.

109
00:08:40.938 --> 00:08:42.856
You didn't have
to blame my bowl.

110
00:08:44.901 --> 00:08:46.611
Come on. You owe me a new one.

111
00:08:55.412 --> 00:08:56.705
All right. that's better.

112
00:08:57.372 --> 00:08:59.582
- I can't get it.
- Are you quitting on me?

113
00:08:59.583 --> 00:09:01.542
It's all marked up. There's
no way I'll scrape those out.

114
00:09:01.543 --> 00:09:03.168
So? It's for the
cupboard. not a museum.

115
00:09:03.169 --> 00:09:05.504
You don't have to pretend. We both
know that it's a piece of shit.

116
00:09:05.505 --> 00:09:09.509
Hey. It's easy enough to
look at what went wrong.

117
00:09:10.218 --> 00:09:12.136
You know. you should
try to take a second.

118
00:09:12.137 --> 00:09:14.514
look a little harder and find
the things to appreciate.

119
00:09:16.558 --> 00:09:20.227
So because my mom doesn't
know what grade I'm in.

120
00:09:20.228 --> 00:09:23.106
I should appreciate that she
knows how to spell my name right?

121
00:09:23.732 --> 00:09:24.815
- Got it.
- Hannah.

122
00:09:24.816 --> 00:09:25.901
No. I'm done.

123
00:09:28.695 --> 00:09:29.696
Hannah.

124
00:09:33.533 --> 00:09:35.535
<i>That's your choice what
you pay attention to.</i>

125
00:10:15.825 --> 00:10:19.578
Hey. What was the name of that restaurant
where your dad worked as a valet?

126
00:10:19.579 --> 00:10:22.499
Remember his story about getting fired
for scratching someone's Porsche?

127
00:10:24.626 --> 00:10:25.918
Sure. Yeah.

128
00:10:25.919 --> 00:10:27.337
You think he made that up?

129
00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:29.964
I mean. he was pretty specific.

130
00:10:29.965 --> 00:10:33.842
Exactly. All these stories your dad
loved to tell about when he was younger.

131
00:10:33.843 --> 00:10:35.261
they can't all be made up.

132
00:10:35.262 --> 00:10:37.263
Some of the details
have to be true.

133
00:10:37.264 --> 00:10:40.182
Like the name of that restaurant. If
we could remember. we could look it up.

134
00:10:40.183 --> 00:10:41.851
Try and find people
who knew him.

135
00:10:43.186 --> 00:10:45.986
Does this make any sense? You're
looking at me like I'm a crazy person.

136
00:10:46.648 --> 00:10:48.984
No. Yeah. I get it. I just...

137
00:10:50.110 --> 00:10:51.569
I don't remember the restaurant.

138
00:10:51.570 --> 00:10:54.029
Okay. What about that
high school boat trip?

139
00:10:54.030 --> 00:10:56.324
The one where he said he got
rescued by the Coast Guard?

140
00:10:57.117 --> 00:10:58.867
I don't think he
told me that one.

141
00:10:58.868 --> 00:11:00.745
Right. I wouldn't have
told you that. either.

142
00:11:01.788 --> 00:11:03.373
Well. now I really
wanna hear it.

143
00:11:04.583 --> 00:11:06.959
Wait. What about that math
professor at Princeton?

144
00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:10.088
The one he brings up when he's
lecturing me about persistence.

145
00:11:10.714 --> 00:11:13.173
Yeah. Dad failed his exam
and the guy framed it.

146
00:11:13.174 --> 00:11:14.925
As a warning for the
rest of the class.

147
00:11:14.926 --> 00:11:17.678
Yeah. And Dad loves to tell me
about how that only motivated him.

148
00:11:17.679 --> 00:11:19.305
which is kind of messed up.

149
00:11:19.306 --> 00:11:21.226
Yeah. He loved that
professor. What was his name?

150
00:11:23.101 --> 00:11:24.019
Tobias something.

151
00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:28.355
Tobias Cocher? Cooker?

152
00:11:28.356 --> 00:11:30.357
Cookman. He called him Cook.

153
00:11:30.358 --> 00:11:34.029
How many math professors can there
be out there named Tobias Cookman?

154
00:11:35.989 --> 00:11:37.282
I see only one.

155
00:11:37.908 --> 00:11:39.074
What's a Fields Medal?

156
00:11:39.075 --> 00:11:42.369
It's like the Nobel Prize
for math. Is he at Princeton?

157
00:11:42.370 --> 00:11:43.747
Not exactly.

158
00:11:49.586 --> 00:11:50.587
Get dressed.

159
00:11:59.346 --> 00:12:00.180
Hey.

160
00:12:00.181 --> 00:12:02.515
Hey. how are you
guys holding up?

161
00:12:03.183 --> 00:12:06.519
- I'm gonna say "no comment".
- <i>Fair enough</i>.

162
00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:08.062
What's going on?

163
00:12:08.063 --> 00:12:11.982
<i>Well. Jake is arguing with the barista
over the milk texture of his latte.</i>

164
00:12:11.983 --> 00:12:15.111
And I'm wondering if Owen kept
any kind of safe in the house.

165
00:12:16.112 --> 00:12:17.112
Safe?

166
00:12:17.113 --> 00:12:18.989
<i>Yeah. the Lady Paul piggy bank.</i>

167
00:12:18.990 --> 00:12:23.203
It had a small Honeywell key inside.
Jake said it's for a fireproof safe.

168
00:12:24.663 --> 00:12:26.081
A secret safe?

169
00:12:26.957 --> 00:12:28.499
Any idea where it might be?

170
00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:32.503
I don't know. His office
or the bedroom closet.

171
00:12:32.504 --> 00:12:35.090
Okay. got it. Anything
else I can do?

172
00:12:36.383 --> 00:12:38.760
Yeah. actually.
Can Jake hear me?

173
00:12:40.470 --> 00:12:41.595
Nope.

174
00:12:41.596 --> 00:12:45.516
Good. Under my bed there is a
duffel. Could you grab it. please?

175
00:12:45.517 --> 00:12:46.935
<i>Yeah. What's inside?</i>

176
00:12:47.686 --> 00:12:49.521
<i>I'm not sure you wanna know</i>.

177
00:12:53.483 --> 00:12:57.319
Hannah Hall. She's traveling with her
stepdaughter. Bailey Michaels. 16.

178
00:12:57.320 --> 00:13:00.614
They were last seen at home
in Sausalito 36 hours ago.

179
00:13:00.615 --> 00:13:02.909
But all signs point
to them skipping town.

180
00:13:03.493 --> 00:13:04.535
Her truck's outside her house.

181
00:13:04.536 --> 00:13:07.913
So. rental car. bus fare. train ticket.
plane ticket. you know the drill.

182
00:13:07.914 --> 00:13:11.917
Track her credit cards. ATM
withdrawals. her boot prints. okay?

183
00:13:11.918 --> 00:13:13.086
We need her location ASAP.

184
00:13:15.463 --> 00:13:17.381
- Rochelle?
- Boss wants to see you.

185
00:13:17.382 --> 00:13:19.425
"Hi. Grady. You're back
early. How was your vacation?"

186
00:13:19.426 --> 00:13:20.719
She sounded pissed.

187
00:13:32.647 --> 00:13:35.942
Who's Hannah Hall? And what the
hell were you doing in Sausalito?

188
00:13:40.822 --> 00:13:42.102
I was coming to talk about that.

189
00:13:42.657 --> 00:13:44.242
You know lying to
me is a felony.

190
00:13:45.201 --> 00:13:46.369
Lying about my vacation?

191
00:13:49.289 --> 00:13:50.290
Speak.

192
00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:17.901
Bailey.

193
00:14:25.784 --> 00:14:28.035
How many medals
did this guy win?

194
00:14:28.036 --> 00:14:29.246
Apparently all of them.

195
00:14:32.791 --> 00:14:37.462
Hi. We're hoping to talk
with Professor Cookman.

196
00:14:38.421 --> 00:14:39.421
Do you have an appointment?

197
00:14:39.422 --> 00:14:41.966
- My father's a former student.
- We're happy to wait.

198
00:14:41.967 --> 00:14:44.426
Well. you're gonna have
to wait somewhere else

199
00:14:44.427 --> 00:14:48.514
'cause his next
avail's on the 24th.

200
00:14:48.515 --> 00:14:49.891
That's two weeks from now.

201
00:14:51.560 --> 00:14:54.437
I'm Hannah. by the way. This
is Bailey. What's your name?

202
00:14:55.105 --> 00:14:56.230
Cheryl.

203
00:14:56.231 --> 00:14:58.441
Hi. Cheryl. Thanks
for taking time.

204
00:14:59.109 --> 00:15:04.947
Especially because Bailey here is one
of the top mathletes in Corpus Christi

205
00:15:04.948 --> 00:15:08.158
and she's torn between going to UT
like her dad and Rice. like her sister.

206
00:15:08.159 --> 00:15:09.285
You see the issue.

207
00:15:09.286 --> 00:15:13.582
if we leave here without seeing Cook
and I lose another child to Rice...

208
00:15:16.251 --> 00:15:20.046
If there's anything you can do to help us
just have a little time with him today.

209
00:15:28.889 --> 00:15:30.222
Cook's teaching right now.

210
00:15:30.223 --> 00:15:33.309
but if you wait outside of class.
you may be able to catch him.

211
00:15:33.310 --> 00:15:35.937
Just don't interrupt
him or make any noise.

212
00:15:36.438 --> 00:15:37.981
Got it. Thank you so much.

213
00:15:42.903 --> 00:15:44.654
A mathlete? Seriously?

214
00:15:45.196 --> 00:15:46.990
Is that your way of
saying you're impressed?

215
00:16:09.429 --> 00:16:11.139
Bailey. wait. We should wait.

216
00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:12.641
Fuck Cheryl.

217
00:16:13.225 --> 00:16:17.478
This matrix. interestingly
enough. iteration of this matrix

218
00:16:17.479 --> 00:16:19.679
- applied to any non-zero vector...
- There's two seats.

219
00:16:24.361 --> 00:16:25.362
Sorry.

220
00:16:27.572 --> 00:16:29.615
I'm sure half of you have
lost your train of thought

221
00:16:29.616 --> 00:16:32.243
and the other half probably
weren't following to begin with.

222
00:16:32.244 --> 00:16:34.204
so let's call it
a day. shall we?

223
00:16:41.878 --> 00:16:44.214
So sorry. Excuse us.

224
00:16:49.344 --> 00:16:50.970
Do you make a habit of
interrupting lectures

225
00:16:50.971 --> 00:16:52.722
or should I consider
myself special?

226
00:16:53.515 --> 00:16:57.560
I'm so sorry. we didn't me... I'm
Hannah Hall. This is Bailey Michaels.

227
00:16:57.561 --> 00:16:58.478
What is it you want?

228
00:16:58.479 --> 00:17:01.272
We're hoping you can help us
identify a former student.

229
00:17:01.273 --> 00:17:03.899
And why would I do that
after you disrupted my class?

230
00:17:03.900 --> 00:17:05.569
You may be the only one who can.

231
00:17:10.156 --> 00:17:11.157
Who's the student?

232
00:17:12.158 --> 00:17:15.661
This is the oldest
photo I have with me.

233
00:17:16.161 --> 00:17:18.539
He would've taken your
class about 26 years ago.

234
00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:20.375
We're hoping you can
remember his name.

235
00:17:21.709 --> 00:17:24.879
You know he took my class 26 years
ago and you don't know his name?

236
00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:28.966
We know what his name is now. but
he changed it. It's complicated.

237
00:17:28.967 --> 00:17:30.594
- In a sentence.
- He's my dad.

238
00:17:31.720 --> 00:17:32.846
And he's missing.

239
00:17:35.265 --> 00:17:37.642
- How'd you trace him back to me?
- He's talked about you.

240
00:17:38.143 --> 00:17:40.186
Apparently you were
his favorite professor.

241
00:17:41.688 --> 00:17:43.314
As nice as that is.

242
00:17:43.315 --> 00:17:46.525
I can't say I recognize him.
I've had thousands of students.

243
00:17:46.526 --> 00:17:49.112
I'm afraid most of them
just tend to blur together.

244
00:17:50.822 --> 00:17:53.241
It would've been your first
or second year teaching.

245
00:17:55.744 --> 00:17:58.120
I don't know about
your memory. Ms. Hall.

246
00:17:58.121 --> 00:18:01.165
but I find the further back
I go. the less I remember.

247
00:18:01.166 --> 00:18:03.668
Perhaps you should try
the registrar's office.

248
00:18:05.587 --> 00:18:07.214
He was the worst
student you ever had.

249
00:18:07.964 --> 00:18:09.965
That's what you told him
when he flunked his midterm.

250
00:18:09.966 --> 00:18:12.009
You actually framed
it. his exam.

251
00:18:12.010 --> 00:18:15.804
You hung it in your office as an example
for other students of what not to do.

252
00:18:15.805 --> 00:18:17.474
Which was cruel. by the way.

253
00:18:18.058 --> 00:18:21.561
But my husband. instead of hating
you. saw it as a challenge.

254
00:18:22.187 --> 00:18:23.563
And then he aced the final.

255
00:18:30.528 --> 00:18:32.168
- May I see that photograph again?
- Yeah.

256
00:18:38.036 --> 00:18:41.831
I can't tell you his
name. but the face.

257
00:18:43.124 --> 00:18:44.459
He looks...

258
00:18:45.919 --> 00:18:49.548
He looks different in my
recollection. Although not entirely.

259
00:18:51.758 --> 00:18:52.801
You said he's missing?

260
00:18:55.303 --> 00:18:56.679
He worked at The Shop.

261
00:18:56.680 --> 00:18:59.891
He disappeared three days ago.
We haven't heard from him since.

262
00:19:01.810 --> 00:19:03.895
Come on. Let's see if we
can get you some answers.

263
00:19:14.322 --> 00:19:15.615
So...

264
00:19:16.866 --> 00:19:19.451
- Not our problem.
- You're kidding me.

265
00:19:19.452 --> 00:19:22.454
- Is Owen Michaels in West Texas?
- I sure as hell hope not.

266
00:19:22.455 --> 00:19:24.540
- Well. then.
- This isn't about where he is.

267
00:19:24.541 --> 00:19:27.042
It's about the fact that if
this office had done its job...

268
00:19:27.043 --> 00:19:30.087
Grady. you're not responsible
for the man's choices.

269
00:19:30.088 --> 00:19:31.463
And neither is this office.

270
00:19:31.464 --> 00:19:35.050
Okay. But if Naomi Wu starts
plastering Owen's face on the news...

271
00:19:35.051 --> 00:19:38.846
Then it'll be added incentive for him to
make better decisions than he did before.

272
00:19:38.847 --> 00:19:41.223
Although I think you've been in
this business long enough to know

273
00:19:41.224 --> 00:19:43.101
that people don't change.

274
00:19:43.894 --> 00:19:45.102
What about the girl?

275
00:19:45.103 --> 00:19:48.272
- All right. she's in serious danger.
- Not if she stays in Sausalito.

276
00:19:48.273 --> 00:19:49.773
You know the kind of
people we're dealing with.

277
00:19:49.774 --> 00:19:51.894
They catch wind of this. it
won't matter where she is.

278
00:19:52.360 --> 00:19:54.195
I guess her father
should've thought of that.

279
00:19:58.867 --> 00:20:00.619
Close the door on the way out.

280
00:20:15.300 --> 00:20:18.720
You'd think I'd remember his name.
having his test hung up like that.

281
00:20:19.971 --> 00:20:22.891
So. it's true? You
really framed it?

282
00:20:24.559 --> 00:20:26.644
You have to understand.
I was young back then.

283
00:20:26.645 --> 00:20:31.440
Barely older than my students. I
thought it would assert my authority.

284
00:20:31.441 --> 00:20:32.984
Why did you take it down?

285
00:20:34.110 --> 00:20:36.695
When my wife saw it.
she wasn't impressed.

286
00:20:36.696 --> 00:20:39.740
She thought it was in poor
taste to take a kid's failure

287
00:20:39.741 --> 00:20:41.493
and parade it like
a prized deer.

288
00:20:42.077 --> 00:20:44.579
- Smart woman.
- Smarter than me. that's for sure.

289
00:20:46.456 --> 00:20:48.791
I found all your final
exams from the '90s.

290
00:20:48.792 --> 00:20:50.001
Thanks.

291
00:20:53.922 --> 00:20:57.258
I'm not sure those will be of much
help. We have blind grading here.

292
00:20:57.259 --> 00:20:58.384
There are no names.

293
00:20:58.385 --> 00:21:00.386
Is there a way to
cross-check the numbers?

294
00:21:00.387 --> 00:21:04.056
Perhaps. Cheryl. check the
filing cabinets in the archives.

295
00:21:04.057 --> 00:21:05.558
See if there's a roster.

296
00:21:05.559 --> 00:21:09.436
And ask the registrar for my
class lists from '96 to '98.

297
00:21:09.437 --> 00:21:10.564
Okay.

298
00:21:13.441 --> 00:21:15.651
I still don't understand
the name change.

299
00:21:15.652 --> 00:21:18.070
How does that fit into the
fraud allegations at his firm?

300
00:21:18.071 --> 00:21:19.864
That's what we're
trying to figure out.

301
00:21:21.032 --> 00:21:24.868
He could've been in some kind of
trouble before The Shop. We don't know.

302
00:21:24.869 --> 00:21:29.164
We're only just learning the differences
between the things he told us and...

303
00:21:29.165 --> 00:21:30.333
The truth?

304
00:21:38.884 --> 00:21:42.428
I can't imagine what you're
going through right now.

305
00:21:42.429 --> 00:21:44.889
but for what it's worth.

306
00:21:44.890 --> 00:21:50.394
there's an old Einstein quote that
always calms me when I'm at a loss.

307
00:21:50.395 --> 00:21:51.396
Einstein?

308
00:21:52.814 --> 00:21:57.068
"So far as the theories of
mathematics are about reality.

309
00:21:57.819 --> 00:21:58.987
they are not certain.

310
00:21:59.613 --> 00:22:01.364
So far as they are certain.

311
00:22:02.407 --> 00:22:04.284
they are not about reality."

312
00:22:05.076 --> 00:22:06.745
Is there a version in English?

313
00:22:07.996 --> 00:22:09.789
Nobody knows shit about shit.

314
00:22:35.815 --> 00:22:36.816
Shit!

315
00:22:37.734 --> 00:22:38.985
How's it going in there?

316
00:22:45.367 --> 00:22:47.118
- What's going on?
- Nothing.

317
00:22:49.329 --> 00:22:50.330
But did Hannah call?

318
00:22:51.665 --> 00:22:52.916
Nope.

319
00:22:55.919 --> 00:22:58.004
Jules. do you know
something that I don't know?

320
00:22:58.505 --> 00:23:00.506
- No.
- Because I am her lawyer.

321
00:23:00.507 --> 00:23:01.674
I'm aware.

322
00:23:01.675 --> 00:23:03.175
Yeah. if there's
something going on.

323
00:23:03.176 --> 00:23:05.719
if the FBI's about to drop a
bomb that I'm not aware of.

324
00:23:05.720 --> 00:23:09.224
- well. then I can't protect her.
- Okay. Calm down.

325
00:23:12.561 --> 00:23:15.355
Owen left Hannah and Bailey
a duffel bag full of cash.

326
00:23:17.357 --> 00:23:18.400
How much cash?

327
00:23:18.984 --> 00:23:21.152
I think a little over a
half a million dollars.

328
00:23:21.987 --> 00:23:25.864
Oh. Jesus Christ. Do you have any idea
how bad this is gonna look to the FBI?

329
00:23:25.865 --> 00:23:28.993
I don't know. Maybe less bad given
that she seems to have misplaced it.

330
00:23:28.994 --> 00:23:30.202
Are you fucking kidding me?

331
00:23:30.203 --> 00:23:33.330
Jules. if Hannah is hiding
money her husband stole.

332
00:23:33.331 --> 00:23:35.374
she's gonna be looking
at a conspiracy charge.

333
00:23:35.375 --> 00:23:38.252
- Obstruction of justice...
- We don't know that Owen stole that money.

334
00:23:38.253 --> 00:23:41.088
Oh. please. Who keeps a half a
million dollars in a duffel bag?

335
00:23:41.089 --> 00:23:42.840
See. this is why she
didn't want me to tell you

336
00:23:42.841 --> 00:23:45.134
because she knew you'd freak
out just like you always do.

337
00:23:45.135 --> 00:23:47.845
Oh. right. So th... It's my fault
she'd rather choose to screw herself

338
00:23:47.846 --> 00:23:49.805
than trust somebody who
actually cares about her.

339
00:23:49.806 --> 00:23:53.059
- She trusted me. Jake. She trusted Owen.
- Look where that got her.

340
00:23:53.810 --> 00:23:56.145
For somebody who has a fear
of getting abandoned again.

341
00:23:56.146 --> 00:23:57.813
she sure does know
how to pick 'em.

342
00:23:57.814 --> 00:24:00.149
Hannah does not have a fear
of being abandoned. okay?

343
00:24:00.150 --> 00:24:01.442
She has a fear of being trapped.

344
00:24:01.443 --> 00:24:03.402
So that's why she
chose not to marry me.

345
00:24:03.403 --> 00:24:07.073
No. Jake. She didn't marry
you because you're an asshole.

346
00:24:10.452 --> 00:24:11.453
Yeah. maybe.

347
00:24:13.163 --> 00:24:15.457
But if I'm such an asshole...

348
00:24:17.959 --> 00:24:19.377
why am I the one who's here?

349
00:24:29.846 --> 00:24:31.681
- Any progress?
- No.

350
00:24:35.560 --> 00:24:36.603
What's this?

351
00:24:37.103 --> 00:24:39.647
Roster for Spring of '97.

352
00:24:39.648 --> 00:24:43.651
You only taught senior seminars in '96
and then only grad students in '98.

353
00:24:43.652 --> 00:24:45.362
so this has to be the class.

354
00:24:45.946 --> 00:24:47.404
Well done. Cheryl.

355
00:24:47.405 --> 00:24:48.490
Thank you.

356
00:24:55.747 --> 00:24:57.958
I'm sorry. These names
aren't sparking anything.

357
00:24:59.834 --> 00:25:02.419
Seventy-three
students. How many men?

358
00:25:02.420 --> 00:25:04.214
Forty-nine. I counted.

359
00:25:04.798 --> 00:25:06.633
That's a hell of a lot
better than a billion.

360
00:25:07.425 --> 00:25:08.785
- May I see it again please?
- Yes.

361
00:25:11.680 --> 00:25:12.681
What?

362
00:25:14.057 --> 00:25:16.476
The young woman. I was
trying to remember her name.

363
00:25:17.060 --> 00:25:18.186
What young woman?

364
00:25:18.770 --> 00:25:22.189
The one he blamed for not being
able to focus on his midterm.

365
00:25:22.190 --> 00:25:25.067
I just remembered he
wrote me this long letter

366
00:25:25.068 --> 00:25:28.821
explaining how he'd fallen in
love with a girl from class.

367
00:25:28.822 --> 00:25:32.117
That he couldn't concentrate
around her. At least. not well.

368
00:25:35.328 --> 00:25:36.830
Could this be her?

369
00:25:40.333 --> 00:25:44.337
I would love to say yes.
but I just don't know.

370
00:25:45.881 --> 00:25:47.591
There's no "Olivia" on the list.

371
00:25:50.343 --> 00:25:52.596
Was that your mother? Olivia?

372
00:25:53.179 --> 00:25:55.307
They met senior year of college.

373
00:25:55.932 --> 00:26:00.311
That's what my dad said. but
maybe it's only half true.

374
00:26:00.312 --> 00:26:01.521
Like everything else.

375
00:26:05.191 --> 00:26:06.735
So. what now?

376
00:26:10.572 --> 00:26:12.949
Cheryl. which library
keeps the yearbooks?

377
00:26:18.538 --> 00:26:20.623
Larry has an update for you on
that woman you asked him t...

378
00:26:20.624 --> 00:26:21.791
Tell him he can drop it.

379
00:26:36.056 --> 00:26:37.557
We're dropping the
Hannah Hall thing?

380
00:26:38.266 --> 00:26:39.975
Yeah. Did you find something?

381
00:26:39.976 --> 00:26:42.437
She and the girl flew out
of SFO yesterday morning.

382
00:26:46.107 --> 00:26:48.068
Are you fucking kidding me?

383
00:26:48.735 --> 00:26:50.111
Are you fucking kidding me?

384
00:26:55.075 --> 00:26:57.369
The yearbooks were
digitized for the archive.

385
00:26:57.869 --> 00:26:59.245
Here's a guest password.

386
00:26:59.246 --> 00:27:02.289
And there is a line of computers
just through the stacks.

387
00:27:02.290 --> 00:27:04.084
Thank you so much for your help.

388
00:27:20.850 --> 00:27:21.935
Hey.

389
00:27:25.730 --> 00:27:27.816
What are we gonna find in there?

390
00:27:29.609 --> 00:27:32.278
- Let's just go sit down.
- No. What are we...

391
00:27:32.279 --> 00:27:34.364
What are we gonna
find out about him?

392
00:27:35.782 --> 00:27:37.409
What are we gonna
find out about me?

393
00:27:38.577 --> 00:27:41.662
- I don't even know who I am.
- Bailey.

394
00:27:41.663 --> 00:27:45.458
The worst part is that
he's always been here.

395
00:27:48.169 --> 00:27:51.131
I didn't even go on a
sleepover until I was ten.

396
00:27:53.300 --> 00:27:54.301
And when I did...

397
00:27:56.428 --> 00:28:01.016
my dad sat in his car and he
waited outside until I went to bed.

398
00:28:02.058 --> 00:28:04.268
just to make sure that
I didn't need him.

399
00:28:04.269 --> 00:28:05.936
He told me that story.

400
00:28:05.937 --> 00:28:08.398
Did he tell you that I
only made it till 7:30?

401
00:28:10.025 --> 00:28:11.026
And then I...

402
00:28:11.943 --> 00:28:16.531
I ran outside and I told
him I wanted to go home.

403
00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:22.746
He's always been there for me.
He said he'd always be there.

404
00:28:24.581 --> 00:28:28.209
- Bailey. I...
- No. Let's just go.

405
00:28:55.654 --> 00:28:57.529
- Go ahead.
- I can call her back.

406
00:28:57.530 --> 00:28:58.615
I'm fine.

407
00:29:01.534 --> 00:29:02.535
I'm fine.

408
00:29:13.505 --> 00:29:15.340
<i>I don't even know who I am.</i>

409
00:29:19.678 --> 00:29:21.555
<i>She doesn't even know who I am.</i>

410
00:29:24.015 --> 00:29:27.851
- That cargo bed is wasted on you.
- Oh. my God. Do you hear yourself?

411
00:29:27.852 --> 00:29:29.979
I'm just saying you
have nothing to pick up.

412
00:29:29.980 --> 00:29:31.730
If this truck were mine...

413
00:29:31.731 --> 00:29:34.316
You still wouldn't be able to
haul your wood turning shit

414
00:29:34.317 --> 00:29:36.485
'cause you still haven't
passed your road test.

415
00:29:36.486 --> 00:29:37.737
Details.

416
00:29:46.830 --> 00:29:48.415
- Is that...
- Thanks for the ride.

417
00:30:27.746 --> 00:30:29.247
What are you doing to my vase?

418
00:30:30.248 --> 00:30:31.582
Improving it.

419
00:30:31.583 --> 00:30:34.919
This was gonna be the piece
that I was remembered for.

420
00:30:34.920 --> 00:30:36.922
My magnum opus.

421
00:30:37.505 --> 00:30:38.590
It really wasn't.

422
00:30:41.301 --> 00:30:43.428
You wanna come in and say
hello before she leaves?

423
00:30:45.597 --> 00:30:47.474
- No. thanks.
- She wants to see you.

424
00:30:48.558 --> 00:30:49.559
Now?

425
00:30:50.060 --> 00:30:53.020
She wants to see me now? She
doesn't even know who I am now.

426
00:30:53.021 --> 00:30:54.773
She's your mother.
She knows you.

427
00:30:57.984 --> 00:30:59.902
Look. she might not
know your friends.

428
00:30:59.903 --> 00:31:02.071
or that you're obsessed
with Emmylou Harris.

429
00:31:02.072 --> 00:31:06.116
Or that you're a terrible driver. but
that's you today. Those things change.

430
00:31:06.117 --> 00:31:08.827
Your music. your friends.
Your driving. God-willing.

431
00:31:08.828 --> 00:31:09.996
What's your point?

432
00:31:11.289 --> 00:31:14.125
My point is. she might
be worth keeping around.

433
00:31:15.544 --> 00:31:18.104
How am I supposed to keep her
around if she's never fucking here?

434
00:31:19.673 --> 00:31:20.674
Hannah.

435
00:31:22.133 --> 00:31:23.134
Hannah. come on.

436
00:31:33.603 --> 00:31:34.854
Grandpa...

437
00:31:36.147 --> 00:31:39.192
for the record. I'm
an excellent driver.

438
00:31:59.671 --> 00:32:02.214
- <i>Hey.</i>
- I think the safe may be in my studio.

439
00:32:02.215 --> 00:32:03.299
Your studio?

440
00:32:03.300 --> 00:32:06.469
<i>Owen knows there's some pieces
I would never sell or give away.</i>

441
00:32:07.304 --> 00:32:09.179
<i>You remember my
grandfather's vase. right?</i>

442
00:32:09.180 --> 00:32:11.015
- <i>Yeah.</i>
- Check the bottom of it.

443
00:32:11.016 --> 00:32:12.100
Will do.

444
00:32:13.643 --> 00:32:17.647
Listen. you're sure that
duffel bag was under your bed?

445
00:32:19.316 --> 00:32:21.151
Positive. Why?

446
00:32:22.777 --> 00:32:24.279
Because it's not there now.

447
00:32:26.114 --> 00:32:28.033
- You sure?
- <i>I'm sure. Han.</i>

448
00:32:28.617 --> 00:32:29.868
What do you want me to do?

449
00:32:34.998 --> 00:32:35.999
Find the safe.

450
00:32:52.432 --> 00:32:53.767
No luck yet. huh?

451
00:33:04.027 --> 00:33:05.028
What?

452
00:33:07.781 --> 00:33:10.324
You know. I was a little
like you when I was your age.

453
00:33:10.325 --> 00:33:12.535
I hadn't really thought
about that before.

454
00:33:14.746 --> 00:33:15.747
Okay.

455
00:33:18.291 --> 00:33:19.584
You don't believe me. do you?

456
00:33:21.711 --> 00:33:26.340
Well. I don't really know who I am now.
so I don't even know what that means.

457
00:33:26.341 --> 00:33:29.135
Hey. I know who you
are. You do too.

458
00:33:30.178 --> 00:33:32.847
Your name. your birthday.
those are just details.

459
00:33:33.682 --> 00:33:35.140
Pretty important details.

460
00:33:35.141 --> 00:33:37.561
Even without everything
that's going on.

461
00:33:38.311 --> 00:33:43.066
plenty of people are gonna try to tell you
who you are or who you're supposed to be.

462
00:33:43.608 --> 00:33:46.194
I'm just saying. I
think you know already.

463
00:33:47.696 --> 00:33:48.779
For what it's worth.

464
00:33:48.780 --> 00:33:51.907
I think you're smart enough to
decide the rest for yourself

465
00:33:51.908 --> 00:33:53.660
and stubborn enough
to stick to it.

466
00:33:59.082 --> 00:34:00.250
You think I'm stubborn?

467
00:34:01.626 --> 00:34:03.587
That's what you
took from all that?

468
00:34:12.554 --> 00:34:14.555
- Hello.
- <i>Scrimmages.</i>

469
00:34:14.556 --> 00:34:16.516
<i>I didn't think about
the scrimmages.</i>

470
00:34:17.099 --> 00:34:18.767
I'm sorry. Who is this?

471
00:34:18.768 --> 00:34:20.810
<i>It's Elenor McGovern
at the church.</i>

472
00:34:20.811 --> 00:34:24.566
You came by yesterday asking
about game day weddings in '11?

473
00:34:25.066 --> 00:34:26.150
Right. Of course.

474
00:34:26.151 --> 00:34:29.486
<i>Well. I told your story to
one of our parishioners and.</i>

475
00:34:29.487 --> 00:34:31.947
well. her older
son is a Longhorn

476
00:34:31.948 --> 00:34:35.701
and she pointed out that it
could've been a pre-season wedding.

477
00:34:35.702 --> 00:34:38.245
And I thought. "Oh my
Lord. am I a dummy."

478
00:34:38.246 --> 00:34:41.248
It never even occurred to
me to check the scrimmages.

479
00:34:41.249 --> 00:34:43.625
Wait. the scrimmages
are held at the stadium?

480
00:34:43.626 --> 00:34:47.337
Just like regular games. that's right.
And they pack the stands pretty good too.

481
00:34:47.338 --> 00:34:50.674
Elenor. did you happen to check
the scrimmage dates for the season?

482
